# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: computability-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] In computability theory, the **Church–Turing thesis** is a thesis about the nature of computable functions.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] It states that a function on the natural numbers can be calculated by an effective method if and only if it is computable by a Turing machine.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The thesis is named after American mathematician Alonzo Church and the British mathematician Alan Turing.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Before the precise definition of computable function, mathematicians often used the informal term *effectively calculable* to describe functions that are computable by paper-and-pencil methods.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Church, Kleene, and Turing proved that these three formally defined classes of computable functions coincide: a function is λ-computable if and only if it is Turing computable, and if and only if it is *general recursive*.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] This has led mathematicians and computer scientists to believe that the concept of computability is accurately characterized by these three equivalent processes.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Other formal attempts to characterize computability have subsequently strengthened this belief (see below).
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] On the other hand, the Church–Turing thesis states that the above three formally defined classes of computable functions coincide with the *informal* notion of an effectively calculable function.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Although the thesis has near-universal acceptance, it cannot be formally proven, as the concept of effective calculability is only informally defined.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Since its inception, variations on the original thesis have arisen, including statements about what can physically be realized by a computer in our universe (physical Church-Turing thesis) and what can be efficiently computed (Church–Turing thesis (complexity theory)).
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] These variations are not due to Church or Turing, but arise from later work in complexity theory and digital physics.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The thesis also has implications for the philosophy of mind (see below).
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Rosser (1939) addresses the notion of "effective computability" as follows: "Clearly the existence of CC and RC [meaning Church's and Rosser's proofs of the statement that there is no effective method for deciding truth] presupposes a precise definition of 'effective'.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] 'Effective method' is here used in the rather special sense of a method each step of which is precisely predetermined and which is certain to produce the answer in a finite number of steps".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Thus the adverb-adjective "effective" is used in a sense of "1a: producing a decided, decisive, or desired effect", and "capable of producing a result".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] In the following, the words "effectively calculable" will mean "produced by any intuitively 'effective' means whatsoever" and "effectively computable" will mean "produced by a Turing-machine or equivalent mechanical device".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The thesis can be stated as: *Every effectively calculable function is a computable function*.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Church also stated that "No computational procedure will be considered as an algorithm unless it can be represented as a Turing Machine".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] One of the important problems for logicians in the 1930s was the *Entscheidungsproblem* of David Hilbert and Wilhelm Ackermann, which asked whether there was a mechanical procedure for separating mathematical truths from mathematical falsehoods.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] This quest required that the notion of "algorithm" or "effective calculability" be pinned down, at least well enough for the quest to begin.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] But from the very outset Alonzo Church's attempts began with a debate that continues to this day.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] In the course of studying the problem, Church and his student Stephen Kleene introduced the notion of λ-definable functions, and they were able to prove that several large classes of functions frequently encountered in number theory were λ-definable.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The debate began when Church proposed to Gödel that one should define the "effectively computable" functions as the λ-definable functions.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Gödel, however, was not convinced and called the proposal "thoroughly unsatisfactory".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Rather, in correspondence with Church (c.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Eventually, he would suggest his recursion, modified by Herbrand's suggestion, that Gödel had detailed in his 1934 lectures in Princeton, New Jersey (Kleene and Rosser transcribed the notes).
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] But he did not think that the two ideas could be satisfactorily identified "except heuristically".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Next, it was necessary to identify and prove the equivalence of two notions of effective calculability.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Equipped with the λ-calculus and "general" recursion, Kleene with help of Church and J.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Barkley Rosser produced proofs (1933, 1935) to show that the two calculi are equivalent.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Church subsequently modified his methods to include use of Herbrand–Gödel recursion and then proved (1936) that the *Entscheidungsproblem* is unsolvable: there is no algorithm that can determine whether a well formed formula has a beta normal form.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Many years later in a letter to Davis (c.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] 1965), Gödel said that "he was, at the time of these [1934] lectures, not at all convinced that his concept of recursion comprised all possible recursions".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] By 1963–1964 Gödel would disavow Herbrand–Gödel recursion and the λ-calculus in favor of the Turing machine as the definition of "algorithm" or "mechanical procedure" or "formal system".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Rather, he regarded the notion of "effective calculability" as merely a "working hypothesis" that might lead by inductive reasoning to a "natural law" rather than by "a definition or an axiom".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] This idea was "sharply" criticized by Church.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Thus, Post in his 1936 paper was also discounting Gödel's suggestion to Church in 1934–1935 that the thesis might be expressed as an axiom or set of axioms.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] In a few years (1939) Turing would propose, like Church and Kleene before him, that *his* formal definition of mechanical computing agent was the correct one.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Thus, by 1939, both Church (1934) and Turing (1939) had individually proposed that their "formal systems" should be *definitions* of "effective calculability"; neither framed their statements as *theses*.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Kleene, finally, uses for the first time the term the "Church-Turing thesis" in a section in which he helps to give clarifications to concepts in Alan Turing's paper "The Word Problem in Semi-Groups with Cancellation", as demanded in a critique from William Boone.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] An attempt to better understand the notion of "effective computability" led Robin Gandy (Turing's student and friend) in 1980 to analyze *machine* computation (as opposed to human-computation acted out by a Turing machine).
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] In the late 1990s Wilfried Sieg analyzed Turing's and Gandy's notions of "effective calculability" with the intent of "sharpening the informal notion, formulating its general features axiomatically, and investigating the axiomatic framework".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] In his 1997 and 2002 work Sieg presents a series of constraints on the behavior of a *computor*—"a human computing agent who proceeds mechanically".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The matter remains in active discussion within the academic community.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The thesis can be viewed as nothing but an ordinary mathematical definition.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Comments by Gödel on the subject suggest this view, e.g.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] "the correct definition of mechanical computability was established beyond any doubt by Turing".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The case for viewing the thesis as nothing more than a definition is made explicitly by Robert I.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Soare, where it is also argued that Turing's definition of computability is no less likely to be correct than the epsilon-delta definition of a continuous function.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Other formalisms (besides recursion, the λ-calculus, and the Turing machine) have been proposed for describing effective calculability/computability.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Kleene (1952) adds to the list the functions "*reckonable* in the system S1" of Kurt Gödel 1936, and Emil Post's (1943, 1946) "*canonical* [also called *normal*] *systems*".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] In the 1950s Hao Wang and Martin Davis greatly simplified the one-tape Turing-machine model (see Post–Turing machine).
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Marvin Minsky expanded the model to two or more tapes and greatly simplified the tapes into "up-down counters", which Melzak and Lambek further evolved into what is now known as the counter machine model.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] In the late 1960s and early 1970s researchers expanded the counter machine model into the register machine, a close cousin to the modern notion of the computer.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Other models include combinatory logic and Markov algorithms.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] All these contributions involve proofs that the models are computationally equivalent to the Turing machine; such models are said to be Turing complete.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Because all these different attempts at formalizing the concept of "effective calculability/computability" have yielded equivalent results, it is now generally assumed that the Church–Turing thesis is correct.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Proofs in computability theory often invoke the Church–Turing thesis in an informal way to establish the computability of functions while avoiding the (often very long) details which would be involved in a rigorous, formal proof.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] In order to make the above example completely rigorous, one would have to carefully construct a Turing machine, or λ-function, or carefully invoke recursion axioms, or at best, cleverly invoke various theorems of computability theory.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] But because the computability theorist believes that Turing computability correctly captures what can be computed effectively, and because an effective procedure is spelled out in English for deciding the set B, the computability theorist accepts this as proof that the set is indeed recursive.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The success of the Church–Turing thesis prompted variations of the thesis to be proposed.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The Church–Turing thesis says nothing about the efficiency with which one model of computation can simulate another.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] It has been proved for instance that a (multi-tape) universal Turing machine only suffers a logarithmic slowdown factor in simulating any Turing machine.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] A variation of the Church–Turing thesis addresses whether an arbitrary but "reasonable" model of computation can be efficiently simulated.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] This is called the **feasibility thesis**, also known as the (**classical**) **complexity-theoretic Church–Turing thesis** or the **extended Church–Turing thesis**, which is not due to Church or Turing, but rather was realized gradually in the development of complexity theory.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] It states: "A probabilistic Turing machine can efficiently simulate any realistic model of computation." The word 'efficiently' here means up to polynomial-time reductions.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] This thesis was originally called **computational complexity-theoretic Church–Turing thesis** by Ethan Bernstein and Umesh Vazirani (1997).
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The complexity-theoretic Church–Turing thesis, then, posits that all 'reasonable' models of computation yield the same class of problems that can be computed in polynomial time.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Assuming the conjecture that probabilistic polynomial time (BPP) equals deterministic polynomial time (P), the word 'probabilistic' is optional in the complexity-theoretic Church–Turing thesis.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] A similar thesis, called the **invariance thesis**, was introduced by Cees F.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] If BQP is shown to be a strict superset of BPP, it would invalidate the complexity-theoretic Church–Turing thesis.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] In other words, there would be efficient quantum algorithms that perform tasks that do not have efficient probabilistic algorithms.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] This would not however invalidate the original Church–Turing thesis, since a quantum computer can always be simulated by a Turing machine, but it would invalidate the classical complexity-theoretic Church–Turing thesis for efficiency reasons.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Eugene Eberbach and Peter Wegner claim that the Church–Turing thesis is sometimes interpreted too broadly, stating "Though [...] Turing machines express the behavior of algorithms, the broader assertion that algorithms precisely capture what can be computed is invalid".
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] They claim that forms of computation not captured by the thesis are relevant today, terms which they call super-Turing computation.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Philosophers have interpreted the Church–Turing thesis as having implications for the philosophy of mind.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] There are also some important open questions which cover the relationship between the Church–Turing thesis and physics, and the possibility of hypercomputation.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The universe is not equivalent to a Turing machine (i.e., the laws of physics are not Turing-computable), but incomputable physical events are not "harnessable" for the construction of a hypercomputer.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] For example, a universe in which physics involves random real numbers, as opposed to computable reals, would fall into this category.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The universe is a hypercomputer, and it is possible to build physical devices to harness this property and calculate non-recursive functions.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] For example, it is an open question whether all quantum mechanical events are Turing-computable, although it is known that rigorous models such as quantum Turing machines are equivalent to deterministic Turing machines.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] (They are not necessarily efficiently equivalent; see above.) John Lucas and Roger Penrose have suggested that the human mind might be the result of some kind of quantum-mechanically enhanced, "non-algorithmic" computation.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] There are many other technical possibilities which fall outside or between these three categories, but these serve to illustrate the range of the concept.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Philosophical aspects of the thesis, regarding both physical and biological computers, are also discussed in Odifreddi's 1989 textbook on recursion theory.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] One can formally define functions that are not computable.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] A well-known example of such a function is the Busy Beaver function.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] This function takes an input *n* and returns the largest number of symbols that a Turing machine with *n* states can print before halting, when run with no input.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Finding an upper bound on the busy beaver function is equivalent to solving the halting problem, a problem known to be unsolvable by Turing machines.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Since the busy beaver function cannot be computed by Turing machines, the Church–Turing thesis states that this function cannot be effectively computed by any method.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Several computational models allow for the computation of (Church-Turing) non-computable functions.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] Mark Burgin argues that super-recursive algorithms such as inductive Turing machines disprove the Church–Turing thesis.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] His argument relies on a definition of algorithm broader than the ordinary one, so that non-computable functions obtained from some inductive Turing machines are called computable.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] This interpretation of the Church–Turing thesis differs from the interpretation commonly accepted in computability theory, discussed above.
[src:computability-theory/church-turing-thesis] The argument that super-recursive algorithms are indeed algorithms in the sense of the Church–Turing thesis has not found broad acceptance within the computability research community.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The study of which mathematical constructions can be effectively performed is sometimes called **recursive mathematics**.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory originated in the 1930s, with the work of Kurt Gödel, Alonzo Church, Rózsa Péter, Alan Turing, Stephen Kleene, and Emil Post.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The fundamental results the researchers obtained established Turing computability as the correct formalization of the informal idea of effective calculation.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] In 1952, these results led Kleene to coin the two names "Church's thesis" and "Turing's thesis".
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Nowadays these are often considered as a single hypothesis, the Church–Turing thesis, which states that any function that is computable by an algorithm is a computable function.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] With a definition of effective calculation came the first proofs that there are problems in mathematics that cannot be effectively decided.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] In 1936, Church and Turing (inspired by techniques used by Gödel to prove his incompleteness theorems) independently demonstrated that the *Entscheidungsproblem* is not effectively decidable.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] This result showed that there is no algorithmic procedure that can correctly decide whether arbitrary mathematical propositions are true or false.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Many problems in mathematics have been shown to be undecidable after these initial examples were established.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] In 1947, Markov and Post published independent papers showing that the word problem for semigroups cannot be effectively decided.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The main form of computability studied in the field was introduced by Turing in 1936.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] A set of natural numbers is said to be a *computable set* (also called a *decidable*, *recursive*, or *Turing computable* set) if there is a Turing machine that, given a number *n*, halts with output 1 if *n* is in the set and halts with output 0 if *n* is not in the set.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] A function *f* from natural numbers to natural numbers is a *(Turing) computable,* or *recursive function* if there is a Turing machine that, on input *n*, halts and returns output *f*(*n*).
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The use of Turing machines here is not necessary; there are many other models of computation that have the same computing power as Turing machines; for example the μ-recursive functions obtained from primitive recursion and the μ operator.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The terminology for computable functions and sets is not completely standardized.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The definition in terms of μ-recursive functions as well as a different definition of *rekursiv* functions by Gödel led to the traditional name *recursive* for sets and functions computable by a Turing machine.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The word *decidable* stems from the German word *Entscheidungsproblem*, which was used in the original papers of Turing and others.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] In contemporary use, the term "computable function" has various definitions: according to Nigel J.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Cutland, it is a partial recursive function (which can be undefined for some inputs), while according to Robert I.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] This article follows the second of these conventions.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] In 1996, Soare gave additional comments about the terminology.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Not every set of natural numbers is computable.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The halting problem, which is the set of (descriptions of) Turing machines that halt on input 0, is a well-known example of a noncomputable set.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The existence of many noncomputable sets follows from the facts that there are only countably many Turing machines, and thus only countably many computable sets, but according to the Cantor's theorem, there are uncountably many sets of natural numbers.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Although the halting problem is not computable, it is possible to simulate program execution and produce an infinite list of the programs that do halt.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Thus the halting problem is an example of a *computably enumerable (c.e.) set*, which is a set that can be enumerated by a Turing machine (other terms for computably enumerable include *recursively enumerable* and *semidecidable*).
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Equivalently, a set is c.e. if and only if it is the range of some computable function.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The c.e. sets, although not decidable in general, have been studied in detail in computability theory.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Beginning with the theory of computable sets and functions described above, the field of computability theory has grown to include the study of many closely related topics.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] These are not independent areas of research: each of these areas draws ideas and results from the others, and most computability theorists are familiar with the majority of them.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory in mathematical logic has traditionally focused on *relative computability*, a generalization of Turing computability defined using oracle Turing machines, introduced by Turing in 1939.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] An oracle Turing machine is a hypothetical device that, in addition to performing the actions of a regular Turing machine, is able to ask questions to an *oracle*, which is a particular set of natural numbers.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The oracle machine may only ask questions of the form "Is *n* in the oracle set?".
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Each question will be immediately answered correctly, even if the oracle set is not computable.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Thus an oracle machine with a noncomputable oracle will be able to compute sets that a Turing machine without an oracle cannot.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Informally, a set of natural numbers *A* is *Turing reducible* to a set *B* if there is an oracle machine that correctly tells whether numbers are in *A* when run with *B* as the oracle set (in this case, the set *A* is also said to be (*relatively*) *computable from* *B* and *recursive in* *B*).
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] If a set *A* is Turing reducible to a set *B* and *B* is Turing reducible to *A* then the sets are said to have the same *Turing degree* (also called *degree of unsolvability*).
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The Turing degree of a set gives a precise measure of how uncomputable the set is.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Each can be translated into any other via a many-one reduction.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] That is, given such sets *A* and *B*, there is a total computable function *f* such that *A* = {*x* : *f*(*x*) ∈ *B*}.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] These sets are said to be *many-one equivalent* (or *m-equivalent*).
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Many-one reducibility is "stronger" than Turing reducibility: if a set *A* is many-one reducible to a set *B*, then *A* is Turing reducible to *B*, but the converse does not always hold.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Although the natural examples of noncomputable sets are all many-one equivalent, it is possible to construct computably enumerable sets *A* and *B* such that *A* is Turing reducible to *B* but not many-one reducible to *B*.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] It can be shown that every computably enumerable set is many-one reducible to the halting problem, and thus the halting problem is the most complicated computably enumerable set with respect to many-one reducibility and with respect to Turing reducibility.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] In 1944, Post asked whether *every* computably enumerable set is either computable or Turing equivalent to the halting problem, that is, whether there is no computably enumerable set with a Turing degree intermediate between those two.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] As intermediate results, Post defined natural types of computably enumerable sets like the simple, hypersimple and hyperhypersimple sets.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Post showed that these sets are strictly between the computable sets and the halting problem with respect to many-one reducibility.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Post also showed that some of them are strictly intermediate under other reducibility notions stronger than Turing reducibility.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] But Post left open the main problem of the existence of computably enumerable sets of intermediate Turing degree; this problem became known as *Post's problem*.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] After ten years, Kleene and Post showed in 1954 that there are intermediate Turing degrees between those of the computable sets and the halting problem, but they failed to show that any of these degrees contains a computably enumerable set.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Very soon after this, Friedberg and Muchnik independently solved Post's problem by establishing the existence of computably enumerable sets of intermediate degree.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] This groundbreaking result opened a wide study of the Turing degrees of the computably enumerable sets, which turned out to possess a very complicated and non-trivial structure.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] There are uncountably many sets that are not computably enumerable, and the investigation of the Turing degrees of all sets is as central in computability theory as the investigation of the computably enumerable Turing degrees.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The study of arbitrary (not necessarily computably enumerable) Turing degrees involves the study of the Turing jump.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Given a set *A*, the *Turing jump* of *A* is a set of natural numbers encoding a solution to the halting problem for oracle Turing machines running with oracle *A*.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The Turing jump of any set is always of higher Turing degree than the original set, and a theorem of Friedburg shows that any set that computes the halting problem can be obtained as the Turing jump of another set.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Post's theorem establishes a close relationship between the Turing jump operation and the arithmetical hierarchy, which is a classification of certain subsets of the natural numbers based on their definability in arithmetic.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Much recent research on Turing degrees has focused on the overall structure of the set of Turing degrees and the set of Turing degrees containing computably enumerable sets.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] A deep theorem of Shore and Slaman states that the function mapping a degree *x* to the degree of its Turing jump is definable in the partial order of the Turing degrees.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] A survey by Ambos-Spies and Fejer gives an overview of this research and its historical progression.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] An ongoing area of research in computability theory studies reducibility relations other than Turing reducibility.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Post introduced several *strong reducibilities*, so named because they imply truth-table reducibility.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] A Turing machine implementing a strong reducibility will compute a total function regardless of which oracle it is presented with.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] *Weak reducibilities* are those where a reduction process may not terminate for all oracles; Turing reducibility is one example.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] via an oracle Turing machine that computes a total function regardless of the oracle it is given.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Many variants of truth-table reducibility have also been studied.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Further reducibilities (positive, disjunctive, conjunctive, linear and their weak and bounded versions) are discussed in the article Reduction (computability theory).
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The major research on strong reducibilities has been to compare their theories, both for the class of all computably enumerable sets as well as for the class of all subsets of the natural numbers.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Furthermore, the relations between the reducibilities has been studied.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] For example, it is known that every Turing degree is either a truth-table degree or is the union of infinitely many truth-table degrees.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Reducibilities weaker than Turing reducibility (that is, reducibilities that are implied by Turing reducibility) have also been studied.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The most well known are arithmetical reducibility and hyperarithmetical reducibility.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] These reducibilities are closely connected to definability over the standard model of arithmetic.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] But, many of these index sets are even more complicated than the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] These type of sets can be classified using the arithmetical hierarchy.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] For example, the index set FIN of the class of all finite sets is on the level Σ2, the index set REC of the class of all recursive sets is on the level Σ3, the index set COFIN of all cofinite sets is also on the level Σ3 and the index set COMP of the class of all Turing-complete sets Σ4.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] These hierarchy levels are defined inductively, Σ*n*+1 contains just all sets that are computably enumerable relative to Σ*n*; Σ1 contains the computably enumerable sets.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The index sets given here are even complete for their levels, that is, all the sets in these levels can be many-one reduced to the given index sets.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The program of *reverse mathematics* asks which set-existence axioms are necessary to prove particular theorems of mathematics in subsystems of second-order arithmetic.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] This study was initiated by Harvey Friedman and was studied in detail by Stephen Simpson and others; in 1999, Simpson gave a detailed discussion of the program.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The set-existence axioms in question correspond informally to axioms saying that the powerset of the natural numbers is closed under various reducibility notions.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The weakest such axiom studied in reverse mathematics is *recursive comprehension*, which states that the powerset of the naturals is closed under Turing reducibility.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] A numbering is an enumeration of functions; it has two parameters, *e* and *x* and outputs the value of the *e*-th function in the numbering on the input *x*.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Numberings can be partial-computable although some of its members are total computable functions.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Admissible numberings are those into which all others can be translated.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] A Friedberg numbering (named after its discoverer) is a one-one numbering of all partial-computable functions; it is necessarily not an admissible numbering.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Later research dealt also with numberings of other classes like classes of computably enumerable sets.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Goncharov discovered for example a class of computably enumerable sets for which the numberings fall into exactly two classes with respect to computable isomorphisms.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Post's problem was solved with a method called the *priority method*; a proof using this method is called a *priority argument*.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] This method is primarily used to construct computably enumerable sets with particular properties.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] To use this method, the desired properties of the set to be constructed are broken up into an infinite list of goals, known as *requirements*, so that satisfying all the requirements will cause the set constructed to have the desired properties.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Each requirement is assigned to a natural number representing the priority of the requirement; so 0 is assigned to the most important priority, 1 to the second most important, and so on.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The set is then constructed in stages, each stage attempting to satisfy one of more of the requirements by either adding numbers to the set or banning numbers from the set so that the final set will satisfy the requirement.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] It may happen that satisfying one requirement will cause another to become unsatisfied; the priority order is used to decide what to do in such an event.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Priority arguments have been employed to solve many problems in computability theory, and have been classified into a hierarchy based on their complexity.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Because complex priority arguments can be technical and difficult to follow, it has traditionally been considered desirable to prove results without priority arguments, or to see if results proved with priority arguments can also be proved without them.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] For example, Kummer published a paper on a proof for the existence of Friedberg numberings without using the priority method.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] When Post defined the notion of a simple set as a c.e. set with an infinite complement not containing any infinite c.e. set, he started to study the structure of the computably enumerable sets under inclusion.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] This lattice became a well-studied structure.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Computable sets can be defined in this structure by the basic result that a set is computable if and only if the set and its complement are both computably enumerable.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Infinite c.e. sets have always infinite computable subsets; but on the other hand, simple sets exist but do not always have a coinfinite computable superset.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Post introduced already hypersimple and hyperhypersimple sets; later maximal sets were constructed, which are c.e. sets such that every c.e. superset is either a finite variant of the given maximal set or is co-finite.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Post's original motivation in the study of this lattice was to find a structural notion such that every set that satisfies this property is neither in the Turing degree of the computable sets nor in the Turing degree of the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Post did not find such a property and the solution to his problem applied priority methods instead; in 1991, Harrington and Soare eventually found such a property.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Another important question is the existence of automorphisms in computability-theoretic structures.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] One of these structures is that one of computably enumerable sets under inclusion modulo finite difference; in this structure, *A* is below *B* if and only if the set difference *B* − *A* is finite.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Maximal sets (as defined in the previous paragraph) have the property that they cannot be automorphic to non-maximal sets, that is, if there is an automorphism of the computably enumerable sets under the structure just mentioned, then every maximal set is mapped to another maximal set.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] In 1974, Soare showed that also the converse holds, that is, every two maximal sets are automorphic.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] So the maximal sets form an orbit, that is, every automorphism preserves maximality and any two maximal sets are transformed into each other by some automorphism.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Harrington gave a further example of an automorphic property: that of the creative sets, the sets that are many-one equivalent to the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Besides the lattice of computably enumerable sets, automorphisms are also studied for the structure of the Turing degrees of all sets as well as for the structure of the Turing degrees of c.e. sets.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The main idea is to consider a universal Turing machine *U* and to measure the complexity of a number (or string) *x* as the length of the shortest input *p* such that *U*(*p*) outputs *x*.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] This approach revolutionized earlier ways to determine when an infinite sequence (equivalently, characteristic function of a subset of the natural numbers) is random or not by invoking a notion of randomness for finite objects.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Kolmogorov complexity became not only a subject of independent study but is also applied to other subjects as a tool for obtaining proofs.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] There are still many open problems in this area.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Such sets are known as (*m*, *n*)-recursive sets.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The first major result in this branch of computability theory is Trakhtenbrot's result that a set is computable if it is (*m*, *n*)-recursive for some *m*, *n* with 2*m* > *n*.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] On the other hand, Jockusch's semirecursive sets (which were already known informally before Jockusch introduced them 1968) are examples of a sets that are (*m*, *n*)-recursive if and only if 2*m* < *n* + 1.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] There are uncountably many of these sets and also some computably enumerable but noncomputable sets of this type.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Later, Degtev established a hierarchy of computably enumerable sets that are (1, *n* + 1)-recursive but not (1, *n*)-recursive.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] After a long phase of research by Russian scientists, this subject became repopularized in the west by Beigel's thesis on bounded queries, which linked frequency computation to the above-mentioned bounded reducibilities and other related notions.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] This is the computability-theoretic branch of learning theory.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Mark Gold's model of learning in the limit from 1967 and has developed since then more and more models of learning.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The general scenario is the following: Given a class *S* of computable functions, is there a learner (that is, computable functional) that outputs for any input of the form (*f*(0), *f*(1), ..., *f*(*n*)) a hypothesis.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] A learner *M* learns a function *f* if almost all hypotheses are the same index *e* of *f* with respect to a previously agreed on acceptable numbering of all computable functions; *M* learns *S* if *M* learns every *f* in *S*.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Basic results are that all computably enumerable classes of functions are learnable while the class REC of all computable functions is not learnable.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Many related models have been considered and also the learning of classes of computably enumerable sets from positive data is a topic studied from Gold's pioneering paper in 1967 onwards.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory includes the study of generalized notions of this field such as arithmetic reducibility, hyperarithmetical reducibility and α-recursion theory, as described by Sacks in 1990.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] These generalized notions include reducibilities that cannot be executed by Turing machines but are nevertheless natural generalizations of Turing reducibility.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] These studies include approaches to investigate the analytical hierarchy, which differs from the arithmetical hierarchy by permitting quantification over sets of natural numbers in addition to quantification over individual numbers.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] These areas are linked to the theories of well-orderings and trees; for example the set of all indices of computable (nonbinary) trees without infinite branches is complete for level $\Pi _{1}^{1}$ of the analytical hierarchy.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Both Turing reducibility and hyperarithmetical reducibility are important in the field of effective descriptive set theory.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The even more general notion of degrees of constructibility is studied in set theory.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory for digital computation is well developed.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory is less well developed for analog computation that occurs in analog computers, analog signal processing, analog electronics, artificial neural networks and continuous-time control theory, modelled by differential equations and continuous dynamical systems.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] For example, models of computation such as the Blum–Shub–Smale machine model have formalized computation on the reals.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] There are close relationships between the Turing degree of a set of natural numbers and the difficulty (in terms of the arithmetical hierarchy) of defining that set using a first-order formula.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] One such relationship is made precise by Post's theorem.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] A weaker relationship was demonstrated by Kurt Gödel in the proofs of his completeness theorem and incompleteness theorems.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Gödel's proofs show that the set of logical consequences of an effective first-order theory is a computably enumerable set, and that if the theory is strong enough this set will be uncomputable.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Similarly, Tarski's indefinability theorem can be interpreted both in terms of definability and in terms of computability.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Computability theory is also linked to second-order arithmetic, a formal theory of natural numbers and sets of natural numbers.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The fact that certain sets are computable or relatively computable often implies that these sets can be defined in weak subsystems of second-order arithmetic.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The program of reverse mathematics uses these subsystems to measure the non-computability inherent in well known mathematical theorems.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] In 1999, Simpson discussed many aspects of second-order arithmetic and reverse mathematics.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The field of proof theory includes the study of second-order arithmetic and Peano arithmetic, as well as formal theories of the natural numbers weaker than Peano arithmetic.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] One method of classifying the strength of these weak systems is by characterizing which computable functions the system can prove to be total.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] For example, in primitive recursive arithmetic any computable function that is provably total is actually primitive recursive, while Peano arithmetic proves that functions like the Ackermann function, which are not primitive recursive, are total.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Not every total computable function is provably total in Peano arithmetic, however; an example of such a function is provided by Goodstein's theorem.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The field of mathematical logic dealing with computability and its generalizations has been called "recursion theory" since its early days.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Soare, a prominent researcher in the field, has proposed that the field should be called "computability theory" instead.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] He argues that Turing's terminology using the word "computable" is more natural and more widely understood than the terminology using the word "recursive" introduced by Kleene.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Many contemporary researchers have begun to use this alternate terminology.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] These researchers also use terminology such as *partial computable function* and *computably enumerable*(*c.e.*)*set* instead of *partial recursive function* and *recursively enumerable*(*r.e.*)*set*.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Not all researchers have been convinced, however, as explained by Fortnow and Simpson.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Some commentators argue that both the names *recursion theory* and *computability theory* fail to convey the fact that most of the objects studied in computability theory are not computable.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] In 1967, Rogers suggested that a key property of computability theory is that its results and structures should be invariant under computable bijections on the natural numbers (this suggestion draws on the ideas of the Erlangen program in geometry).
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The idea is that a computable bijection merely renames numbers in a set, rather than indicating any structure in the set, much as a rotation of the Euclidean plane does not change any geometric aspect of lines drawn on it.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] Since any two infinite computable sets are linked by a computable bijection, this proposal identifies all the infinite computable sets (the finite computable sets are viewed as trivial).
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] According to Rogers, the sets of interest in computability theory are the noncomputable sets, partitioned into equivalence classes by computable bijections of the natural numbers.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The main professional organization for computability theory is the *Association for Symbolic Logic*, which holds several research conferences each year.
[src:computability-theory/computability-theory] The interdisciplinary research Association *Computability in Europe* (*CiE*) also organizes a series of annual conferences.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] In computability theory and computational complexity theory, a **decision problem** is a computational problem that can be posed as a yes–no question on a set of input values.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] An example of a decision problem is deciding whether a given natural number is prime.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] A **decision procedure** for a decision problem is an algorithmic method that answers the yes-no question on all inputs, and a decision problem is called **decidable** if there is a decision procedure for it.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] For example, the decision problem "given two numbers *x* and *y*, does *x* evenly divide *y*?" is decidable since there is a decision procedure called long division that gives the steps for determining whether *x* evenly divides *y* and the correct answer, *YES* or *NO*, accordingly.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Some of the most important problems in mathematics are **undecidable**, e.g. the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] The field of computational complexity theory categorizes *decidable* decision problems by how difficult they are to solve.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] "Difficult", in this sense, is described in terms of the computational resources needed by the most efficient algorithm for a certain problem.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] On the other hand, the field of recursion theory categorizes *undecidable* decision problems by Turing degree, which is a measure of the noncomputability inherent in any solution.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] A *decision problem* is the formal language of all inputs for which the output (the answer to the yes-no question on a given input) is *YES*.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] A classic example of a decidable decision problem is the set of prime numbers.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] It is possible to effectively decide whether a given natural number is prime by testing every possible nontrivial factor.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Although much more efficient procedures of primality testing are known, the existence of any effective procedure is enough to establish decidability.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Problems that are not decidable are *undecidable*, which means it is not possible to create an algorithm (efficient or not) that solves them.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] The halting problem is an important undecidable decision problem; for more examples, see list of undecidable problems.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Decision problems can be ordered according to many-one reducibility and related to feasible reductions such as polynomial-time reductions.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] A decision problem *P* is said to be *complete* for a set of decision problems *S* if *P* is a member of *S* and every problem in *S* can be reduced to *P*.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Complete decision problems are used in computational complexity theory to characterize complexity classes of decision problems.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] For example, the Boolean satisfiability problem is complete for the class NP of decision problems under polynomial-time reducibility.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Decision problems are closely related to function problems, which can have answers that are more complex than a simple *YES* or *NO*.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] A corresponding function problem is "given two numbers *x* and *y*, what is *x* divided by *y*?".
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] A function problem consists of a partial function *f*; the informal "problem" is to compute the values of *f* on the inputs for which it is defined.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Every function problem can be turned into a decision problem; the decision problem is just the graph of the associated function.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] (The graph of a function *f* is the set of pairs (*x*,*y*) such that *f*(*x*) = *y*.) If this decision problem were effectively solvable then the function problem would be as well.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] This reduction does not respect computational complexity, however.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] For example, it is possible for the graph of a function to be decidable in polynomial time (in which case running time is computed as a function of the pair (*x*,*y*)) when the function is not computable in polynomial time (in which case running time is computed as a function of *x* alone).
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] The function *f*(*x*) = 2*x* has this property.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Every decision problem can be converted into the function problem of computing the characteristic function of the set associated to the decision problem.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] If this function is computable then the associated decision problem is decidable.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Unlike decision problems, for which there is only one correct answer for each input, optimization problems are concerned with finding the *best* answer to a particular input.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Optimization problems arise naturally in many applications, such as the traveling salesman problem and many questions in linear programming.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Function and optimization problems are often transformed into decision problems by considering the question of whether the output is *equal to* or *less than or equal to* a given value.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] This allows the complexity of the corresponding decision problem to be studied; and in many cases the original function or optimization problem can be solved by solving its corresponding decision problem.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] For example, in the traveling salesman problem, the optimization problem is to produce a tour with minimal weight.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] The associated decision problem is: for each *N*, to decide whether the graph has any tour with weight less than *N*.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] By repeatedly answering the decision problem, it is possible to find the minimal weight of a tour.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Because the theory of decision problems is very well developed, research in complexity theory has typically focused on decision problems.
[src:computability-theory/decision-problem] Optimization problems themselves are still of interest in computability theory, as well as in fields such as operations research.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In computability theory, the **halting problem** is the decision problem of determining, from a description of an arbitrary computer program and an input, whether the program will eventually halt (finish running) or continue to run forever.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Alan Turing proved in 1937 that the halting problem is *undecidable*, meaning that no general algorithm exists that can correctly solve the problem for all possible program–input pairs.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The problem comes up often in discussions of computability since it demonstrates that some functions are mathematically definable but not computable.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] A key part of the formal statement of the problem is a mathematical definition of a computer and program, usually via a Turing machine.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The proof then shows, for any program *f* that might determine whether programs halt, that a "pathological" program *g* exists for which *f* makes an incorrect determination.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Specifically, *g* is the program that, when called with some input, passes its own source and its input to *f* and does the opposite of what *f* predicts *g* will do.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The behavior of *f* on *g* shows undecidability as it means no program *f* will solve the halting problem in every possible case.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The halting problem is a decision problem about properties of computer programs on a fixed Turing-complete model of computation.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This model of computation includes all programs in Turing-equivalent programming languages.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Given a program and an input, the question is whether the program will eventually halt when run with that particular input.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In this abstract framework, there are no limitations on the memory or time required for the program's execution; the program may run arbitrarily long and consume arbitrarily large amounts of storage before halting.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] never halts; rather, it goes on forever in an infinite loop.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Simple cases like these are easy to decide, but more complex programs are not.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Turing proved no algorithm exists that always correctly decides whether, for a given arbitrary program and input, the program halts when run with that input.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The essence of Turing's proof is that any such algorithm can be made to produce contradictory output and therefore cannot be correct.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Some infinite loops can be quite useful.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] For instance, event loops are typically coded as infinite loops.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Most subroutines, however, are intended to finish.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In hard real-time computing, subroutines must not only finish, but finish before a given deadline.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In order to meet these requirements, programmers apply the rule of least power and use restricted styles, not quite fully Turing-complete, that make it easy to prove that the resulting subroutines finish before the given deadline.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] These include languages such as MISRA C, SPARK, and Rocq.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The halting problem requires a decision procedure that works for all programs and inputs.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] But for any specific program and input, the answer is simply "halts" or "does not halt".
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Consider two simple decision procedures, one that always answers "halts" and another that always answers "does not halt".
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] For any given case, one of these two algorithms answers correctly, yet neither algorithm solves the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Interpreters are programs that simulate the execution of programs whatever source code they are given.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Such programs can demonstrate that a program does halt, by running the program for some number of steps.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] However, an interpreter will not halt if its input program does not halt, so this approach cannot solve the halting problem as stated; it does not successfully answer "does not halt" for programs that do not halt, or determine whether a program will eventually halt or run forever.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The halting problem is decidable for linear bounded automata (LBAs) or deterministic machines with finite memory.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] For nondeterministic finite memory machines, it is also decidable whether the machine halts on none, some, or all of the possible sequences of nondeterministic decisions, by enumerating states after each possible decision.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In April 1936, Alonzo Church published his proof of the undecidability of a problem in the lambda calculus.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Turing's proof was published later, in January 1937.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Since then, many other undecidable problems have been described, including the halting problem which emerged in the 1950s.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Many papers and textbooks refer the definition and proof of undecidability of the halting problem to Turing's 1936 paper.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Turing did not use the terms "halt" or "halting" in any of his published works, including his 1936 paper.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] A search of the academic literature from 1936 to 1958 showed that the first published material using the term "halting problem" was Rogers (1957).
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] However, Rogers says he had a draft of Davis (1958) available to him, and Martin Davis states in the introduction that "the expert will perhaps find some novelty in the arrangement and treatment of topics", so the terminology must be attributed to Davis.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Davis stated in a letter that he had been referring to the halting problem since 1952.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The halting problem is Turing equivalent to both Davis's printing problem ("does a Turing machine starting from a given state ever print a given symbol?") and to the printing problem considered in Turing's 1936 paper ("does a Turing machine starting from a blank tape ever print a given symbol?").
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] However, Turing equivalence is rather loose and does not mean that the two problems are the same.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] There are machines which print but do not halt, and halt but not print.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The printing and halting problems address different issues and exhibit important conceptual and technical differences.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In theoretical computer science, a decision problem is any problem that can be phrased as a yes–no question about a mathematical object.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Given the description of a program (P) and an input (x), does (P(x)) eventually halt?
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The conventional representation of decision problems is the set of objects possessing the property in question.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This set is recursively enumerable, which means there is a computable function that lists all of the pairs (*i*, *x*) it contains.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] However, the complement of this set is not recursively enumerable.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] A decision problem is said to be *decidable* if there exists an algorithm that always halts with the correct answer, and an undecidable problem if no such algorithm exists.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In his original proof Turing formalized the concept of *algorithm* by introducing Turing machines.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] However, the result is in no way specific to them; it applies equally to any other model of computation that is equivalent in its computational power to Turing machines, such as Markov algorithms, Lambda calculus, Post systems, register machines, or tag systems.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] What is important is that the formalization allows a straightforward mapping of algorithms to some data type that the algorithm can operate upon.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The mapping to strings is usually the most straightforward, but strings over an alphabet with *n* characters can also be mapped to numbers by interpreting them as numbers in an *n*-ary numeral system.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] There are many undecidable problems; any set whose Turing degree equals that of the halting problem is such a formulation.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Christopher Strachey outlined a proof by contradiction that the halting problem is not solvable.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The proof proceeds as follows: Suppose that there exists a total computable function *halts(f)* that returns true if the subroutine *f* halts (when run with no inputs) and returns false otherwise.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The concept above shows the general method of the proof, but the computable function *halts* does not directly take a subroutine as an argument; instead it takes the source code of a program.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Moreover, the definition of *g* is self-referential.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] A rigorous proof addresses these issues.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Here *program i* refers to the *i* th program in an enumeration of all the programs of a fixed Turing-complete model of computation.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Possible values for a total computable function *f* arranged in a 2D array.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The values of *f*(*i*,*i*) and *g*(*i*) are shown at the bottom; *U* indicates that the function *g* is undefined for a particular input value.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The proof proceeds by directly establishing that no total computable function with two arguments can be the required function *h*.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Because *g* is partial computable, there must be a program *e* that computes *g*, by the assumption that the model of computation is Turing-complete.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This program is one of all the programs on which the halting function *h* is defined.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The next step of the proof shows that *h*(*e*,*e*) will not have the same value as *f*(*e*,*e*).
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In either case, *f* cannot be the same function as *h*.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Because *f* was an *arbitrary* total computable function with two arguments, all such functions must differ from *h*.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This proof is analogous to Cantor's diagonal argument.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] One may visualize a two-dimensional array with one column and one row for each natural number, as indicated in the table above.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The value of *f*(*i*,*j*) is placed at column *i*, row *j*.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Because *f* is assumed to be a total computable function, any element of the array can be calculated using *f*.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The construction of the function *g* can be visualized using the main diagonal of this array.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] If the array has a 0 at position (*i*,*i*), then *g*(*i*) is 0.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The contradiction comes from the fact that there is some column *e* of the array corresponding to *g* itself.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Now assume *f* was the halting function *h*.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Similarly, if *g*(*e*) is not defined, then program *e* does not halt on input *e*, thus *f*(*e,e*) = 0, which leads to *g*(*e*) = 0 under *g'*s construction.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This contradicts the assumption of *g*(*e*) not being defined.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Therefore any arbitrary computable function *f* cannot be the halting function *h*.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] A typical method of proving a problem P to be undecidable is to *reduce* the halting problem to P .
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] For example, there cannot be a general algorithm that decides whether a given statement about natural numbers is true or false.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The reason for this is that the proposition stating that a certain program will halt given a certain input can be converted into an equivalent statement about natural numbers.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] If an algorithm could find the truth value of every statement about natural numbers, it could certainly find the truth value of this one; but that would determine whether the original program halts.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Rice's theorem generalizes the theorem that the halting problem is unsolvable.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] It states that for *any* non-trivial property, there is no general decision procedure that, for all programs, decides whether the partial function implemented by the input program has that property.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] (A partial function is a function which may not always produce a result, and so is used to model programs, which can either produce results or fail to halt.) For example, the property "halt for the input 0" is undecidable.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Here, "non-trivial" means that the set of partial functions that satisfy the property is neither the empty set nor the set of all partial functions.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] For example, "halt on input 0 within 100 steps" is *not* a property of the partial function that is implemented by the program—it is a property of the program implementing the partial function and is very much decidable.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Gregory Chaitin has defined a halting probability, represented by the symbol Ω, a type of real number that informally is said to represent the probability that a randomly produced program halts.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] These numbers have the same Turing degree as the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] It is a normal and transcendental number which can be defined but cannot be completely computed.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This means one can prove that there is no algorithm which produces the digits of Ω, although its first few digits can be calculated in simple cases.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Since the negative answer to the halting problem shows that there are problems that cannot be solved by a Turing machine, the Church–Turing thesis limits what can be accomplished by any machine that implements effective methods.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] However, not all machines conceivable to human imagination are subject to the Church–Turing thesis (e.g. oracle machines).
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] It is also an open question whether any such unknown physical processes are involved in the working of the human brain, and whether humans can solve the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Turing's proof shows that there can be no mechanical, general method (i.e., a Turing machine or a program in some equivalent model of computation) to determine whether algorithms halt.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] However, each individual instance of the halting problem has a definitive answer, which may or may not be practically computable.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Given a specific algorithm and input, one can often show that it halts or does not halt, and in fact computer scientists often do just that as part of a correctness proof.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] There are some heuristics that can be used in an automated fashion to attempt to construct a proof, which frequently succeed on typical programs.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This field of research is known as automated termination analysis.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Some results have been established on the theoretical performance of halting problem heuristics, in particular the fraction of programs of a given size that may be correctly classified by a recursive algorithm.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] These results do not give precise numbers because the fractions are uncomputable and also highly dependent on the choice of program encoding used to determine "size".
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] For example, consider classifying programs by their number of states and using a specific "Turing semi-infinite tape" model of computation that errors (without halting) if the program runs off the left side of the tape.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Then $\lim _{n\to \infty }P(x\,{\text{halts is decidable}}\mid x\,{\text{has}}\,n\,{\text{states}})=1$ , over programs x chosen uniformly by number of states.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] But this result is in some sense "trivial" because these decidable programs are simply the ones that fall off the tape, and the heuristic is simply to predict not halting due to error.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Thus a seemingly irrelevant detail, namely the treatment of programs with errors, can turn out to be the deciding factor in determining the fraction of programs.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] To avoid these issues, several restricted notions of the "size" of a program have been developed.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] For example, a numbering that assigns indices $2^{n}$ to nontrivial programs and all other indices the error state is not dense, but there exists a dense Gödel numbering of syntactically correct Brainfuck programs.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] A dense Gödel numbering is called optimal if, for any other Gödel numbering $\alpha$ , there is a 1-1 total recursive function f and a constant c such that for all i , $\alpha _{i}=\phi _{f(i)}$ and $f(i)\leq ci$ .
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This condition ensures that all programs have indices not much larger than their indices in any other Gödel numbering.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Optimal Gödel numberings are constructed by numbering the inputs of a universal Turing machine.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] A third notion of size uses universal machines operating on binary strings and measures the length of the string needed to describe the input program.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] A universal machine *U* is a machine for which every other machine *V* there exists a total computable function h such that $V(x)=U(h(x))$ .
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] An optimal machine is a universal machine that achieves the Kolmogorov complexity invariance bound, i.e. for every machine *V*, there exists *c* such that for all outputs *x*, if a *V*-program of length *n* outputs *x*, then there exists a *U*-program of at most length $n+c$ outputting *x*.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] We consider partial computable functions (algorithms) A .
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The complex nature of these bounds is due to the oscillatory behavior of $\epsilon _{n}(A)$ .
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] There are infrequently occurring new varieties of programs that come in arbitrarily large "blocks", and a constantly growing fraction of repeats.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] If the blocks of new varieties are fully included, the error rate is at least $\epsilon$ , but between blocks the fraction of correctly categorized repeats can be arbitrarily high.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In particular a "tally" heuristic that simply remembers the first N inputs and recognizes their equivalents allows reaching an arbitrarily low error rate infinitely often.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The concepts raised by Gödel's incompleteness theorems are very similar to those raised by the halting problem, and the proofs are quite similar.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In fact, a weaker form of the First Incompleteness Theorem is an easy consequence of the undecidability of the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This weaker form differs from the standard statement of the incompleteness theorem by asserting that an effective axiomatization of the natural numbers that is both complete and sound is impossible.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The "sound" part is the weakening: it means that we require the axiomatic system in question to prove only *true* statements about natural numbers.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Since soundness implies consistency, this weaker form can be seen as a corollary of the strong form.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] It is important to observe that the statement of the standard form of Gödel's First Incompleteness Theorem is completely unconcerned with the truth value of a statement, but only concerns the issue of whether it is possible to find it through a mathematical proof.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The weaker form of the theorem can be proved from the undecidability of the halting problem as follows.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Assume that we have a sound (and hence consistent) and complete effective axiomatization of all true first-order logic statements about natural numbers.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Then we can build an algorithm that enumerates all these statements.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This means that there is an algorithm *N*(*n*) that, given a natural number *n*, computes a true first-order logic statement about natural numbers, and that for all true statements, there is at least one *n* such that *N*(*n*) yields that statement.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Now suppose we want to decide if the algorithm with representation *a* halts on input *i*.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] We know that this statement can be expressed with a first-order logic statement, say *H*(*a*, *i*).
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Since the axiomatization is complete it follows that either there is an *n* such that *N*(*n*) = *H*(*a*, *i*) or there is an *n′* such that *N*(*n′*) = ¬ *H*(*a*, *i*).
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] So if we iterate over all *n* until we either find *H*(*a*, *i*) or its negation, we will always halt, and furthermore, the answer it gives us will be true (by soundness).
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This means that this gives us an algorithm to decide the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Since we know that there cannot be such an algorithm, it follows that the assumption that there is a sound and complete effective axiomatization of all true first-order logic statements about natural numbers must be false.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Many variants of the halting problem can be found in computability textbooks.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Typically, these problems are RE-complete and describe sets of complexity $\Sigma _{1}^{0}$ in the arithmetical hierarchy, the same as the standard halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The variants are thus undecidable, and the standard halting problem reduces to each variant and vice-versa.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] However, some variants have a higher degree of unsolvability and cannot be reduced to the standard halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The *universal halting problem*, also known (in recursion theory) as *totality*, is the problem of determining whether a given computer program will halt *for every input* (the name *totality* comes from the equivalent question of whether the computed function is total).
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This problem is not only undecidable, as the halting problem is, but highly undecidable.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] In terms of the arithmetical hierarchy, it is $\Pi _{2}^{0}$ -complete.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] This means, in particular, that it cannot be decided even with an oracle for the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] There are many programs that, for some inputs, return a correct answer to the halting problem, while for other inputs they do not return an answer at all.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] However the problem "given program *p*, is it a partial halting solver" (in the sense described) is at least as hard as the halting problem.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] To see this, assume that there is an algorithm PHSR ("partial halting solver recognizer") to do that.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] Then it can be used to solve the halting problem, as follows: To test whether input program *x* halts on *y*, construct a program *p* that on input (*x*,*y*) reports *true* and diverges on all other inputs.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] A *lossy Turing machine* is a Turing machine in which part of the tape may non-deterministically disappear.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] The halting problem is decidable for a lossy Turing machine but non-primitive recursive.
[src:computability-theory/halting-problem] A machine with an oracle for the halting problem can determine whether particular Turing machines will halt on particular inputs, but they cannot determine, in general, whether machines equivalent to themselves will halt.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The first condition suggests why the term *semidecidable* is sometimes used.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] More precisely, if a number is in the set, one can *decide* this by running the algorithm, but if the number is not in the set, the algorithm can run forever, and no information is returned.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] A set that is "completely decidable" is a computable set.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The second condition suggests why *computably enumerable* is used.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The abbreviations **c.e.** and **r.e.** are often used, even in print, instead of the full phrase.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] In computational complexity theory, the complexity class containing all computably enumerable sets is RE.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] In recursion theory, the lattice of c.e. sets under inclusion is denoted ${\mathcal {E}}$ .
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] A set *S* of natural numbers is called **computably enumerable** if there is a partial computable function whose domain is exactly *S*, meaning that the function is defined if and only if its input is a member of *S*.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The equivalence of semidecidability and enumerability can be obtained by the technique of dovetailing.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The Diophantine characterizations of a computably enumerable set, while not as straightforward or intuitive as the first definitions, were found by Yuri Matiyasevich as part of the negative solution to Hilbert's Tenth Problem.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] Diophantine sets predate recursion theory and are therefore historically the first way to describe these sets (although this equivalence was only remarked more than three decades after the introduction of computably enumerable sets).
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] If *A* and *B* are computably enumerable sets then *A* ∩ *B*, *A* ∪ *B* and *A* × *B* (with the ordered pair of natural numbers mapped to a single natural number with the Cantor pairing function) are computably enumerable sets.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The preimage of a computably enumerable set under a partial computable function is a computably enumerable set.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] A set T is called **co-computably-enumerable** or **co-c.e.** if its complement $\mathbb {N} \setminus T$ is computably enumerable.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] Equivalently, a set is co-r.e. if and only if it is at level $\Pi _{1}^{0}$ of the arithmetical hierarchy.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The complexity class of co-computably-enumerable sets is denoted co-RE.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] A set *A* is computable if and only if both *A* and the complement of *A* are computably enumerable.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] Some pairs of computably enumerable sets are effectively separable and some are not.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The set of all recursively enumerable subsets of the natural numbers can be made into a poset under set inclusion; this poset is a lattice.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The theory of this lattice is known to be an undecidable problem.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] Similarly, the set of all computably enumerable vector spaces also forms a lattice.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] In fact, one can generalize this even further to the lattice *L(Q)*, which is defined to consist of all recursively enumerable filters, where *Q* is some free Boolean algebra without any atoms.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] These lattices are closely tied to the study of recursively enumerable Pi-0-1 classes.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The intervals of this lattice are either boolean algebras, or their first-order theory is also undecidable.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The possible structure of intervals of this lattice is not very well understood.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The complement of the function which enumerates any maximal recursively enumerable set dominates every general recursive function.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] There exists maximal recursively enumerable set of Turing degree at most **0′**.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] For any two maximal recursively enumerable sets *A* and *B*, there exists an order automorphism of the lattice of recursively enumerable sets that maps *A* to *B*; this automorphism, however, may not always be computable.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] According to the Church–Turing thesis, any effectively calculable function is calculable by a Turing machine, and thus a set *S* is computably enumerable if and only if there is some algorithm which yields an enumeration of *S*.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] This cannot be taken as a formal definition, however, because the Church–Turing thesis is an informal conjecture rather than a formal axiom.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] The definition of a computably enumerable set as the *domain* of a partial function, rather than the *range* of a total computable function, is common in contemporary texts.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] This choice is motivated by the fact that in generalized recursion theories, such as α-recursion theory, the definition corresponding to domains has been found to be more natural.
[src:computability-theory/recursively-enumerable-set] Other texts use the definition in terms of enumerations, which is equivalent for computably enumerable sets.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] A **Turing machine** is a mathematical model of computation describing an abstract machine that manipulates symbols on a strip of tape according to a table of rules.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Despite the model's simplicity, it is capable of implementing any computer algorithm.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The machine operates on an infinite memory tape divided into discrete cells, each of which can hold a single symbol drawn from a finite set of symbols called the alphabet of the machine.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] It has a "head" that, at any point in the machine's operation, is positioned over one of these cells, and a "state" selected from a finite set of states.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] At each step of its operation, the head reads the symbol in its cell.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Then, based on the symbol and the machine's own present state, the machine writes a symbol into the same cell, and moves the head one step to the left or the right, or halts the computation.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The choice of which replacement symbol to write, which direction to move the head, and whether to halt is based on a finite table that specifies what to do for each combination of the current state and the symbol that is read.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] As with a real computer program, it is possible for a Turing machine to go into an infinite loop which will never halt.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The Turing machine was invented in 1936 by Alan Turing, who called it an "a-machine" (automatic machine).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] It was Turing's doctoral advisor, Alonzo Church, who later coined the term "Turing machine" in a review.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Turing machines proved the existence of fundamental limitations on the power of mechanical computation.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] While they can express arbitrary computations, their minimalist design makes them too slow for computation in practice: real-world computers are based on different designs that, unlike Turing machines, use random-access memory.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Turing completeness is the ability for a model of computation or a system of instructions to simulate a Turing machine.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] A programming language that is Turing complete is theoretically capable of expressing all tasks accomplishable by computers; nearly all programming languages are Turing complete if the limitations of finite memory are ignored.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] A Turing machine is an idealised model of a central processing unit (CPU) that controls all data manipulation done by a computer, with the canonical machine using sequential memory to store data.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Typically, the sequential memory is represented as a tape of infinite length on which the machine can perform read and write operations.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In the context of formal language theory, a Turing machine (automaton) is capable of enumerating some arbitrary subset of valid strings of an alphabet.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] A set of strings which can be enumerated in this manner is called a recursively enumerable language.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The Turing machine can equivalently be defined as a model that recognises valid input strings, rather than enumerating output strings.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Given a Turing machine *M* and an arbitrary string *s*, it is generally not possible to decide whether *M* will eventually produce *s*.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] This is due to the fact that the halting problem is unsolvable, which has major implications for the theoretical limits of computing.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] A Turing machine that is able to simulate any other Turing machine is called a universal Turing machine (UTM, or simply a universal machine).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Another mathematical formalism, lambda calculus, with a similar "universal" nature was introduced by Alonzo Church.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Church's work intertwined with Turing's to form the basis for the Church–Turing thesis.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Studying the abstract properties of Turing machines has yielded many insights into computer science, computability theory, and complexity theory.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The Turing machine mathematically models a machine that mechanically operates on a tape.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] On this tape are symbols, which the machine can read and write, one at a time, using a tape head.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Operation is fully determined by a finite set of elementary instructions such as "in state 42, if the symbol seen is 0, write a 1; if the symbol seen is 1, change into state 17; in state 17, if the symbol seen is 0, write a 1 and change to state 6"; etc.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Move the head (which is described by dk and can have values: 'L' for one step left *or* 'R' for one step right *or* 'N' for staying in the same place).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Assume the same or a *new state* as prescribed (go to state qi1).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In the 4-tuple models, erasing or writing a symbol (aj1) and moving the head left or right (dk) are specified as separate instructions.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The table tells the machine to (ia) erase or write a symbol *or* (ib) move the head left or right, *and then* (ii) assume the same or a new state as prescribed, but not both actions (ia) and (ib) in the same instruction.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In some models, if there is no entry in the table for the current combination of symbol and state, then the machine will halt; other models require all entries to be filled.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] A variant allows "no shift", say N, as a third element of the set of directions $\{L,R\}$ .
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Initially all tape cells are marked with 0 .
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Definitions in literature sometimes differ slightly, to make arguments or proofs easier or clearer, but this is always done in such a way that the resulting machine has the same computational power.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] For example, the set could be changed from $\{L,R\}$ to $\{L,R,N\}$ , where *N* ("None" or "No-operation") would allow the machine to stay on the same tape cell instead of moving left or right.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] This would not increase the machine's computational power.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] For the remainder of this article "definition 1" (the Turing/Davis convention) will be used.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In the following table, Turing's original model allowed only the first three lines that he called N1, N2, N3.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] He allowed for erasure of the "scanned square" by naming a 0th symbol S0 = "erase" or "blank", etc.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] However, he did not allow for non-printing, so every instruction-line includes "print symbol Sk" or "erase".
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Any Turing table (list of instructions) can be constructed from the above nine 5-tuples.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] For technical reasons, the three non-printing or "N" instructions (4, 5, 6) can usually be dispensed with.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] For examples see Turing machine examples.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Less frequently the use of 4-tuples are encountered: these represent a further atomization of the Turing instructions.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The word "state" used in context of Turing machines can be a source of confusion, as it can mean two things.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Most commentators after Turing have used "state" to mean the name/designator of the current instruction to be performed—i.e. the contents of the state register.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] But Turing (1936) made a strong distinction between a record of what he called the machine's "m-configuration", and the machine's (or person's) "state of progress" through the computation—the current state of the total system.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Earlier in his paper Turing carried this even further: he gives an example where he placed a symbol of the current "m-configuration" —the instruction's label— beneath the scanned square, together with all the symbols on the tape.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] He calls it "the *complete configuration*".
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] To print the "complete configuration" on one line, he places the state-label/m-configuration to the *left* of the scanned symbol.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] But Kleene refers to "q4" itself as "the machine state".
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Hopcroft and Ullman call this composite the "instantaneous description" and follow the Turing convention of putting the "current state" (instruction-label, m-configuration) to the *left* of the scanned symbol (p.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] 149), that is, the instantaneous description is the composite of non-blank symbols to the left, state of the machine, the current symbol scanned by the head, and the non-blank symbols to the right.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] This means: after three moves the tape has ...
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] 000110000 ... on it, the head is scanning the right-most 1, and the state is *A*.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Blanks (in this case represented by "0"s) can be part of the total state as shown here: *B*01; the tape has a single 1 on it, but the head is scanning the 0 ("blank") to its left and the state is *B*.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] To the right: the above table as expressed as a "state transition" diagram.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Usually large tables are better left as tables (Booth, p.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] They are more readily simulated by computer in tabular form (Booth, p.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] However, certain concepts—e.g. machines with "reset" states and machines with repeating patterns (cf.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] 244ff)—can be more readily seen when viewed as a drawing.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Whether a drawing represents an improvement on its table must be decided by the reader for the particular context.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The reader should again be cautioned that such diagrams represent a snapshot of their table frozen in time, *not* the course ("trajectory") of a computation *through* time and space.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] While every time the busy beaver machine "runs" it will always follow the same state-trajectory, this is not true for the "copy" machine that can be provided with variable input "parameters".
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The diagram "progress of the computation" shows the three-state busy beaver's "state" (instruction) progress through its computation from start to finish.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] On the far right is the Turing "complete configuration" (Kleene "situation", Hopcroft–Ullman "instantaneous description") at each step.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] If the machine were to be stopped and cleared to blank both the "state register" and entire tape, these "configurations" could be used to rekindle a computation anywhere in its progress.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Many machines that might be thought to have more computational capability than a simple universal Turing machine can be shown to have no more power (Hopcroft and Ullman p.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] They might compute faster, perhaps, or use less memory, or their instruction set might be smaller, but they cannot compute more powerfully (i.e. more mathematical functions).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] A Turing machine is equivalent to a single-stack pushdown automaton (PDA) that has been made more flexible and concise by relaxing the last-in-first-out (LIFO) requirement of its stack.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In addition, a Turing machine is also equivalent to a two-stack PDA with standard LIFO semantics, by using one stack to model the tape left of the head and the other stack for the tape to the right.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] At the other extreme, some very simple models turn out to be Turing-equivalent, i.e. to have the same computational power as the Turing machine model.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Read-only, right-moving Turing machines are equivalent to DFAs (as well as NFAs by conversion using the NFA to DFA conversion algorithm).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] For practical and didactic intentions, the equivalent register machine can be used as a usual assembly programming language.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] A relevant question is whether or not the computation model represented by concrete programming languages is Turing equivalent.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] While the computation of a real computer is based on finite states and thus not capable to simulate a Turing machine, programming languages themselves do not necessarily have this limitation.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Kirner et al., 2009 have shown that among the general-purpose programming languages some are Turing complete while others are not.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] For example, ANSI C is not Turing complete, as all instantiations of ANSI C (different instantiations are possible as the standard deliberately leaves certain behaviour undefined for legacy reasons) imply a finite-space memory.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] This is because the size of memory reference data types, called *pointers*, is accessible inside the language.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] However, other programming languages like Pascal do not have this feature, which allows them to be Turing complete in principle.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] It is just Turing complete in principle, as memory allocation in a programming language is allowed to fail, which means the programming language can be Turing complete when ignoring failed memory allocations, but the compiled programs executable on a real computer cannot.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Turing (1936) does not elaborate further except in a footnote in which he describes how to use an a-machine to "find all the provable formulae of the [Hilbert] calculus" rather than use a choice machine.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] He "suppose[s] that the choices are always between two possibilities 0 and 1.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Each proof will then be determined by a sequence of choices i1, i2, ..., in (i1 = 0 or 1, i2 = 0 or 1, ..., in = 0 or 1), and hence the number 2n + i12n-1 + i22n-2 + ... +in completely determines the proof.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] This is indeed the technique by which a deterministic (i.e., a-) Turing machine can be used to mimic the action of a nondeterministic Turing machine; Turing solved the matter in a footnote and appears to dismiss it from further consideration.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] An oracle machine or o-machine is a Turing a-machine that pauses its computation at state "**o**" while, to complete its calculation, it "awaits the decision" of "the oracle"—an entity unspecified by Turing "apart from saying that it cannot be a machine" (Turing (1939)).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The model of computation that Turing called his "universal machine"—"**U**" for short—is considered by some to have been the fundamental theoretical breakthrough that led to the notion of the stored-program computer.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In terms of computational complexity, a multi-tape universal Turing machine need only be slower by logarithmic factor compared to the machines it simulates.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Turing machines are more powerful than some other kinds of automata, such as finite-state machines and pushdown automata.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] According to the Church–Turing thesis, they are as powerful as real machines, and are able to execute any operation that a real program can.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] What is neglected in this statement is that, because a real machine can only have a finite number of *configurations*, it is nothing but a finite-state machine, whereas a Turing machine has an unlimited amount of storage space available for its computations.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] A limitation of Turing machines is that they do not model the strengths of a particular arrangement well.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] For instance, modern stored-program computers are actually instances of a more specific form of abstract machine known as the random-access stored-program machine or RASP machine model.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Like the universal Turing machine, the RASP stores its "program" in "memory" external to its finite-state machine's "instructions".
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Unlike the universal Turing machine, the RASP has an infinite number of distinguishable, numbered but unbounded "registers"—memory "cells" that can contain any integer (cf.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Elgot and Robinson (1964), Hartmanis (1971), and in particular Cook-Rechow (1973); references at random-access machine).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The RASP's finite-state machine is equipped with the capability for indirect addressing (e.g., the contents of one register can be used as an address to specify another register); thus the RASP's "program" can address any register in the register-sequence.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] An example of this is binary search, an algorithm that can be shown to perform more quickly when using the RASP model of computation rather than the Turing machine model.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In the early days of computing, computer use was typically limited to batch processing, i.e., non-interactive tasks, each producing output data from given input data.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Computability theory, which studies computability of functions from inputs to outputs, and for which Turing machines were invented, reflects this practice.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Since the 1970s, interactive use of computers became much more common.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In principle, it is possible to model this by having an external agent read from the tape and write to it at the same time as a Turing machine, but this rarely matches how interaction actually happens; therefore, when describing interactivity, alternatives such as I/O automata are usually preferred.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Some algorithms run in polynomial time in one model but not in the other one.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] However, if an algorithm runs in polynomial time in the arithmetic model, and in addition, the binary length of all involved numbers is polynomial in the length of the input, then it is always polynomial-time in the Turing model.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Such an algorithm is said to run in strongly polynomial time.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Gandy's analysis of Babbage's analytical engine describes the following five operations (cf. p.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Any sequence of operations is an operation.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Iteration of an operation (repeating n times an operation P).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Conditional iteration (repeating n times an operation P conditional on the "success" of test T).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Conditional transfer (i.e., conditional "goto").
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] With regard to Hilbert's problems posed by the famous mathematician David Hilbert in 1900, an aspect of problem #10 had been floating about for almost 30 years before it was framed precisely.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] By 1922, this notion of "Entscheidungsproblem" had developed a bit, and H.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] By the 1928 international congress of mathematicians, Hilbert "made his questions quite precise.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Second, was mathematics *consistent* ...
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] And thirdly, was mathematics *decidable*?" The first two questions were answered in 1930 by Kurt Gödel at the very same meeting where Hilbert delivered his retirement speech (much to the chagrin of Hilbert); the third—the Entscheidungsproblem—had to wait until the mid-1930s.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] The problem was that an answer first required a precise definition of "definite general applicable prescription", which Princeton professor Alonzo Church would come to call "effective calculability", and in 1928 no such definition existed.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] But over the next 6–7 years Emil Post developed his definition of a worker moving from room to room writing and erasing marks per a list of instructions, as did Church and his two students Stephen Kleene and J.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Rosser by use of Church's lambda-calculus and Gödel's recursion theory (1934).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Church's paper (published 15 April 1936) showed that the Entscheidungsproblem was indeed "undecidable" and beat Turing to the punch by almost a year (Turing's paper submitted 28 May 1936, published January 1937).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In the meantime, Emil Post submitted a brief paper in the fall of 1936, so Turing at least had priority over Post.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] While Church refereed Turing's paper, Turing had time to study Church's paper and add an Appendix where he sketched a proof that Church's lambda-calculus and his machines would compute the same functions.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Post had only proposed a definition of calculability and criticised Church's "definition", but had proved nothing.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In the spring of 1935, Turing as a young Master's student at King's College, Cambridge, took on the challenge; he had been stimulated by the lectures of the logician M.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Newman "and learned from them of Gödel's work and the Entscheidungsproblem ...
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] While Gandy believed that Newman's statement above is "misleading", this opinion is not shared by all.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Turing had a lifelong interest in machines: "Alan had dreamt of inventing typewriters as a boy; [his mother] Mrs.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Turing had a typewriter; and he could well have begun by asking himself what was meant by calling a typewriter 'mechanical'" (Hodges p.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] While at Princeton pursuing his PhD, Turing built a Boolean-logic multiplier (see below).
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Alan Turing invented the "a-machine" (automatic machine) in 1936.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Turing submitted his paper on 31 May 1936 to the London Mathematical Society for its *Proceedings*, but it was published in early 1937 and offprints were available in February 1937.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Thus by providing a mathematical description of a very simple device capable of arbitrary computations, he was able to prove properties of computation in general—and in particular, the uncomputability of the *Entscheidungsproblem* ('decision problem').
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Arguments still continue concerning the origin and nature of what has been named by Kleene (1952) Turing's Thesis.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] — from Turing's paper as reprinted in *The Undecidable*, p.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Turing's example (his second proof): If one is to ask for a general procedure to tell us: "Does this machine ever print 0", the question is "undecidable".
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] In 1937, while at Princeton working on his PhD thesis, Turing built a digital (Boolean-logic) multiplier from scratch, making his own electromechanical relays (Hodges p.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] "Alan's task was to embody the logical design of a Turing machine in a network of relay-operated switches ..." (Hodges p.
[src:computability-theory/turing-machine] Today, the counter, register and random-access machines and their sire the Turing machine continue to be the models of choice for theorists investigating questions in the theory of computation.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] In computability theory and computational complexity theory, an **undecidable problem** is a decision problem for which it is proved to be impossible to construct an algorithm that always leads to a correct yes-or-no answer.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] The halting problem is an example: it can be proven that there is no algorithm that correctly determines whether an arbitrary program eventually halts when run.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] A decision problem is a question which, for every input in some infinite set of inputs, requires a "yes" or "no" answer.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Those inputs can be numbers (for example, the decision problem "is the input a prime number?") or values of some other kind, such as strings of a formal language.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] The formal representation of a decision problem is a subset of the natural numbers.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] For decision problems on natural numbers, the set consists of those numbers that the decision problem answers "yes" to.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] For example, the decision problem "is the input even?" is formalized as the set of even numbers.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] A decision problem whose input consists of strings or more complex values is formalized as the set of numbers that, via a specific Gödel numbering, correspond to inputs that satisfy the decision problem's criteria.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] A decision problem *A* is called decidable or effectively solvable if the formalized set of *A* is a recursive set.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] A problem is called partially decidable, semi-decidable, solvable, or provable if *A* is a recursively enumerable set.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] and a finite input, decide whether the program finishes running or will run forever.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Alan Turing proved in 1936 that a general algorithm running on a Turing machine that solves the halting problem for *all* possible program-input pairs necessarily cannot exist.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Hence, the halting problem is *undecidable* for Turing machines.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Undecidable problems can be related to different topics, such as logic, abstract machines or topology.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Since there are uncountably many undecidable problems, any list, even one of infinite length, is necessarily incomplete.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] There are two distinct senses of the word "undecidable" in contemporary use.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] The first of these is the sense used in relation to Gödel's theorems, that of a statement being neither provable nor refutable in a specified deductive system.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] The second sense is used in relation to computability theory and applies not to statements but to decision problems, which are countably infinite sets of questions each requiring a yes or no answer.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Such a problem is said to be undecidable if there is no computable function that correctly answers every question in the problem set.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] The connection between these two is that if a decision problem is undecidable (in the recursion theoretical sense) then there is no consistent, effective formal system which proves for every question *A* in the problem either "the answer to *A* is yes" or "the answer to *A* is no".
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Because of the two meanings of the word undecidable, the term independent is sometimes used instead of undecidable for the "neither provable nor refutable" sense.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] The usage of "independent" is also ambiguous, however.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] It can mean just "not provable", leaving open whether an independent statement might be refuted.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Undecidability of a statement in a particular deductive system does not, in and of itself, address the question of whether the truth value of the statement is well-defined, or whether it can be determined by other means.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Undecidability only implies that the particular deductive system being considered does not prove the truth or falsity of the statement.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Whether there exist so-called "absolutely undecidable" statements, whose truth value can never be known or is ill-specified, is a controversial point among various philosophical schools.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] One of the first problems suspected to be undecidable, in the second sense of the term, was the word problem for groups, first posed by Max Dehn in 1911, which asks if there is a finitely presented group for which no algorithm exists to determine whether two words are equivalent.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] This was shown to be the case in 1955 by Sergei Novikov.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] These results do not require the incompleteness theorem.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Gödel proved in 1940 that neither of these statements could be disproved in ZF or ZFC set theory.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] In the 1960s, Cohen proved that neither is provable from ZF, and the continuum hypothesis cannot be proven from ZFC.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Hilbert's Tenth Problem, posed in 1900 as a challenge to the next century of mathematicians, was proved undecidable by Yuri Matiyasevich in 1970.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Hilbert's challenge sought an algorithm which finds all solutions of a Diophantine equation.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] A Diophantine equation is a more general case of Fermat's Last Theorem; we seek integer roots of a polynomial in any number of variables with integer coefficients.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Since we have only one equation but *n* variables, infinitely many solutions exist (and are easy to find) in the complex plane; however, the problem becomes impossible if solutions are constrained to integer values of the variables.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Matiyasevich showed this problem to be unsolvable by mapping a Diophantine equation to a recursively enumerable set and invoking Gödel's Incompleteness Theorem.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] In 1936, Alan Turing proved that the halting problem—the question of whether or not a Turing machine halts on a given program—is undecidable, in the second sense of the term.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] This result was later generalized by Rice's theorem.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] In 1973, Saharon Shelah showed the Whitehead problem in group theory is undecidable, in the first sense of the term, in standard set theory.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] In 1977, Paris and Harrington proved that the Paris-Harrington principle, a version of the Ramsey theorem, is undecidable in the axiomatization of arithmetic given by the Peano axioms but can be proven to be true in the larger system of second-order arithmetic.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Kruskal's tree theorem, which has applications in computer science, is also undecidable from the Peano axioms but provable in set theory.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] In fact Kruskal's tree theorem (or its finite form) is undecidable in a much stronger system codifying the principles acceptable on basis of a philosophy of mathematics called predicativism.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Goodstein's theorem is a statement about the Ramsey theory of the natural numbers that Kirby and Paris showed is undecidable in Peano arithmetic.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Gregory Chaitin produced undecidable statements in algorithmic information theory and proved another incompleteness theorem in that setting.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Chaitin's theorem states that for any theory that can represent enough arithmetic, there is an upper bound *c* such that no specific number can be proven in that theory to have Kolmogorov complexity greater than *c*.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] While Gödel's theorem is related to the liar paradox, Chaitin's result is related to Berry's paradox.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] In 2007, researchers Kurtz and Simon, building on earlier work by J.H.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] Conway in the 1970s, proved that a natural generalization of the Collatz problem is undecidable.
[src:computability-theory/undecidable-problem] In 2019, Ben-David and colleagues constructed an example of a learning model (named EMX), and showed a family of functions whose learnability in EMX is undecidable in standard set theory.
